titleStmt.title: Istanbul, Topkapı Palace Museum (Topkapı Sarayı Müzesi), "Emanet 13" (Gotthelf Bergsträßer archives) [= Karatay 59]

respStmt.resp: Edited by Michael Marx in collaboration with Tobias J. Jocham et. al. TEI version created by Yasmin Faghihi and Huw Jones

msIdentifier.repository: Topkapı Palace Museum (Topkapı Sarayı Müzesi) , Istanbul

summary.p: Black-and-white photos of 216 fol. in Gotthelf Bergsträßer's archives [according to F. Karatay: 216 fol.]; Parchment; Shelfmark: "Emanet 13" (Gotthelf Bergsträßer archives) [= Karatay 59 E.H. 5]; complete text of the Qurʾān; 20 lines per page; Dimensions: 308 x 305 mm [according to Karatay, no. 59, E.H. 5]; Script style: kūfī, type B.Ib; Estimated date of production: 650-750 CE (?). Gotthelf Bergsträßer's archives contain black-and-white photos of 216 folios of a complete early codex of the Qurʾān. All images show double pages of the opened codex; in this catalogue entry for each page, one image with the individual page (image no. 1) together with the initial photo of the opened codex (image no. 2) is given. The catalogue of Arabic manuscripts of Topkapı Sarayı Palace (Topkapı Sarayı Müzesi Kütüphanesi Türkçe Yazmalar Kataloğu [I–II], I. Din, tarih, bilimler, Istanbul 1961), written by Fehmi E. Karatay, mentions under shelfmark "E.H. 5" a codex that probably corresponds to what is labelled as "Emanet 13" in Bergsträßer's archives.

Karatay (p. 21) gives the following information: "no. 59 E.H. 5 Aynı Parṣömen. 308mm boy ve 305mm eninde 216 yaprak. Sahifede kûfî yazı ile 240mm uzunl. 20 satır. Tahminen III-IV, (IX-X) asırda istinsah edilmiştir. Sure isimleri kırmızı ile yazılmıṣtır. Miklep ve yazma şemseli siya deri Osmanlı cildi. Tam bir kuran nushasıdır." The number of folios and the line number correspond to the codex on the black-and-white photos, the dimensions seem to match with the images as well. Karatay suggests a date within the 9th-10th centuries (3rd-4th centuries AH) which appears to be a late date estimate with regard to the early page design in vertical format and the ancient script style (kūfī B) of this manuscript. The script style shares features with manuscripts Leiden, Cod.or. 14.545a (a fragment of the same codex to which Paris, Arabe 335 initially had belonged). Carbon dating of this manuscript suggests a date between ca. 650 and 775 CE, with a high probability for a date before 700. Without access to the original codex preserved in the Topkapı Palace collection, it is difficult to suggest a date estimate. Based on the evidence of the photos, and with regard to carbon dating of Leiden, Cod.or. 14.545a, "Emanet 13" (E.H. 5) could be one of the most ancient existing complete codices of the Qurʾān.

Images from the black-and-white film rolls have been digitized by Tobias J. Jocham, and prepared for the database by Farah C. Artika. Qurʾānic text ranges have been identified in collaboration with Manssur Karamzadeh. As folio numbers are not explicitely given in the photos of Bergsträßer's archives, the numbers of folios are counted from Q 1 (fol. 1v) to Q 114 (fol. 216r).

The script style of this Qurʾān manuscript is the early kūfī B.Ib (Déroche 1992: PN 38-39). The shaft of the letter ʾalif is vertical; the isolated form has a horizontal return at the baseline. The letter group ǧīm/ḥāʾ/ḫāʾ in the independent and final form has a small horizontal tail which ends with a short hook. The ʿayn in the final form shows a different form of its tail, which has a longer return than in other B.Ib copies.
The original diacritical marks are indicated by small dashes. There seems to be a second layer of the diacritical marking with small dots. (Salome Beridze)
